HOUSE PRESIDENTS WANT
LIBERAL ROLES LEGALLY
The following statement was read at the open Senate meeting Wednesday by West morris House President John files.
We, the members of the Council of House treatments and of
the Associated Women Students Board, both as individual leaders
and as representative of student interest and opinion, believe that
an expression of open forms is integral to the replication of social
and intellectual goals of‘the College, and wish to state our Syﬂ'h
paths with the dissatisiaction of those who would now declare their
independence from present college social regulations. We must object, however, to any infectious. irresponsible, or potentially managing method proposed as an initial effort to achieve social reform.
We believe that [he opens question constitutes a valid issue in it<
self. but that it is but one of several important areas of college
life with which we and the general community should be concerned.
Moreover, in the consideration oi any proposal for significant generation in present social or academic conditions we respect and
fully recognize the necessity for maintaining facultyrstudent and
administration-student support as essential to the ordered pursuit or
progressive changes in the college environment.
We would like to state our conviction that the present open
forms rule is a restriction which not only is unecessary to the
safety and wellrbelng of members of the college community, but
also is seriously inhibilive to a desirable development of individual!
who can accept. or be challenged to accept, the ultimate responsibility for their actions and for the respect which is due to others.
To us the structural features of this college have already contributed much to containing a sheltered sort of environment in
which parochialism, restricted portions, and individual investors‘
bility can develop, survive. and flooring, We believe that we must
and should make a concerned effort as student leaders and genres
sentatives to impose and remove unreasonable restriction on the
individual. We therefore commit ourselves to a program ot pro<
quest and iruitiul discussions with Student, faculty, and administra<
tiny. of such issues as the institution of an alternative form
structure. the possibility for academic revision, and a significant
relaxation of existing social regulatory.
The present rules on open forms constitute, to us, a reasonable social restriction. We export the administration and faculty to
respect the poverty of our criticisms, to listen with open minds to
our expressions oi multiﬁnation, and to be reception to reasonable
arguments and requests for any reform. in the dealtime, we reassert our medication to pursue the changes initially through tale existing legal system
