THE COLLEGE CABIN
The college cabin at Rock Creek is being sold. The state Wants
ID expand the facilities at the State Park, and is in the process of
purchasing the land owned by the college
The loss of the Cabin is opportunity for Grinnell students. although the steel and often buddy path from the road and the
outcomes restrict facilities character somewhat from the cabin’s
popularity, it provided on adequate shelter, privacy. and — most
important —- was primarily owned. '
The State Park closes at 10:30 pm, and imposed restrictions
on cooking ﬁres. Other parks with adequate theaters and cooking
facilities are at a potentially prospective distance for casual use.
There are two questions arising from the coming sale of the
cabin. Since the sale is not even near the final stages, why can’t
we use the Cabin this Fall? Lee Arbetman, North Campus Social
Chairman, was told by Dean centers that the Cabin was in need
of repair. We were told last Fall that the cabin was in need of
repair, yet it was used. Arbetman offered in help pay for repairs
from the social fund, but centers said the cabin was closed peru
recently.
The second question involves the future of oiiscampus property
for social programming. According to Mr. zambia, business manager of the college, there has been no discussion of purchasing any
property to replace Lake Acre.
Loss of the cabin Is a further restriction on already limited opportunities for social activities. Failure to secure a new location
for an off»calcium cabin would be unlorgivable.
REVOLUTION
The September Revolution was shortliveo. Worried house
Iimsidenls stood before their mistress blocks, and explained that
‘suggest was ready ID let It third of the faculty and twothirds of
the students go" in order to maintain the secretary of the rule:
over upskirt students.
The passes were pulled. A catalog of possible college improve—
meets was read at Wednesday’s open Senate meeting by pic
MacDowell. At that same meeting, Chairman of the Faculty Wall
[aid that the Curriculum Committee reply should reach the students in November.
The activists returned to the underground, Part of their work
had been successful. The idea of revolution had been installed
upon the minds or the members or the college community.
Few of us would welcome an open revolution and its necessary
repercussions; however, even fewer of us are satisfied with cold
ieee social regulations as they stand now. Somewhere between
revolution and maintaining the status que lies the desirable course
for discrimination. IT We really believe that social rules change is
important, let us not be times about steering closer to the former.
