MACDGWELL SCCCESTS MANY AREAS FOR CAMPUS COMMUNITY CONCERN
More important than any one rule is the concept oi a total view oi our college
and the ideals we feel it should strike for. There are some, however, who change
at the very thought oi general philosophy and demand action rather total words. We
heartily sympathize with them, for we recognize the necessary need for action and
yet can not move in any direction until we decide what our end results should he
and how they will direct us in both shortrrange and long-range perspectives.
As an institution, Grinncll’s primary responsibility is academic. We are here to
be educated. Yet, education is list the process in which a professor lectures and the
student reports those lectures when called upon in a final exam. Education is active.
it demands an exchange oi knowing where the professor leads his puppy as both or
them search in an attempt to find an understanding. And it is knowing, not. known<
edge, for knowledge is terminal while knowing is pi-ocessive and continuous. it is
country productive, and that is what makes it exciting and relevant. We can learn
from every person who compounds us. And all of this learning should have as its goal“
the preparation oi the learned for iiie — not academics, but life in a real world at
sweet and fear and problem Too often we ignore this here at Grinnell; but that
should he education's primary purpose, especially in a small liberal arts college.
The change toward this which we must take comes in two areas: First the curriculum. This fall as Mr. Wall has stated, We will receive a report by the curriculum
committee. We should use this as a jumping-oil point for improving Grilineil. We
can not tear radicalism in make g charges, for we need it. The teacher-puppy rely»
township is poor for many factors. Why not have all lectures limited and handed out,
then spend the usual lecture time in meaningful class discussion? Change the
curriculum to make us think. Add a new course in 20th Century American mytiis
in which we would drive into the bytes oi our time which we are perpetuating. and
seek some solutions to them. How about going outside oi our narrow concepts oi
Western society and setting up courses in Asian studies? Cut down graduation credit
requirements so more time can be spent in meaningful work outside the classroom.
Set up community action pi-ogiams where students could work in a ghetto for a
semester and get full credit. li we are going to have programs like the ACM semester or year in Latin America, then one participating should receive incl credit
rather than squirting with dept. heads who don't like the program, and receiving
only partial credit, working them to spend extra time in undergraduate work. We
must make our curriculum come: alive and bring excitement into the most. routine
“intro” courses. The enthustasm of a likely bull session should be present in ARH,
but this takes concerned community eiioi-t, especially on the part oi a willing faculty
ready to make necessary changes.
However, changes are not only essential in the curriculum. Since we are a re.'
central college. oils total living situation should enhance and complement what has<
pens in our class rooms. Our present living situation does not . . . in {act it relates
it. The hardcover from the classroom to the form is ml, How many students know
a professor well enough that they feel he could write a recommendation about them
as people, not academicians? How many students actually try to build this necessary
support? How many faculty members deliberately she away from it, feeling that
their job is one which stops when the bell rings? Look at the inadequacy oi our academic counseling system. How many faculty counseling can recognize their students
by sight and call them by their first names? Why not change the present system and
set up one where competent upperclassmen council in both the academic and social
area, then have those truly interested faculty members serve as general hall contractors who work will) the student counseling, using their skills, plus those of the
psychiatric climb and oiir administrative counseling to set up a really worthwhile
program. l-house treatments should be encouraged to invite processors to balls to talk
intormally as people. not centuries. What's wrong with seniors and others visiting
press up to their rooms for a beer and a bull session? We must be willing to work
will] each other as individuals, not separate groups of faculty, students and administration. We have a community and must act in the context of that comments, not
the way we alone feel.
To me a principal education does not pi'email students for like, because it does
not help them to relate to other people. Besides a better relationship among faculty,
administration, and students, we need a better relationship among students themselves. Our social system with an unnatural several on of men and women in a bored
campus . . . reiniorced by separate eating places, sends to aggregate us. People
don’t feel at ease with one another. There is a lack of meaningful interaction and
a lack oi respect. We area't really open to each other, but narrowly reject or
accept people on a supervision basis. The sites seem to get together for normal
dating only, arranged in advance and go only to what the college calendar sets
down. We complete that social events area’t what. We want, and yet We don‘t upon<
laneoiisly try to set up our own. The Senate initiative fund is there to provide in-
central for exactly this and hills a revision in the procedure for using it, hopefully
we will find more creativity and spontaneity in the social area. Our shine Forum, for
the price it cost, has a stability in it which reinforces the structuralism which We
are attempting to remove. The South Lounge is a place for creative discussion, yet
you can’t speak above a whether and the piano is only played on formal occasions.
So we need changes in our social structure. Although there is a gossip 'ty oi getting central red dining in the near future, maybe we should investigate alternative
of forms as a better solution. integrating the computer so you see a man or Woman,
and feel you can manually talk to someone oi the opposite sex without calling up a
week in advance. I've heard lots or people say that alternative would be great —
just so i don‘t have to leave my hall or be separated from my hall brother — per.
maps we should start by investigation the parochialism in our own hall system.
Also within the context oi social relationships the lack oi opportunity for each
oi us to 'meet in a situated where we can meaningfully relate both as couples and
as informal groups. Besides the inconvenience which is caused by a lack oi opens.
the individual’s ability to modern his behavior and accept necessary responsibility is
happened. With these ideas in mind the student house treatments, recognize that
the problems in these two obvious areas, the academic and the social, must be
solved. We see the appropriate means or action through organized channels in which
we consider the immediate and future effects of our decision. The COfl-‘lP-AWS Board
plans to indicate discussion Within the college community which will result Within
a matter oi weeks with a specific proposal to the senate. Here the work oi the
CDHP and AWS in the area of rule change can be supplemental and reinforced.
But there are other areas of importance, some of which seem mandate alter the
sensationalism oi opens, htit which are important. We need to form a Senate committee to nvestigate and ivory- out grevieuces with Saga. We need to set tip a new
system of course evaluation, perhaps including written teacher evaluation, available
to the residents. We need to investigate the possibility of changing the time for elections to allow new officers mon‘c tliTlE to get oriented. We need to look into the World
around us and set up talking about the Vietnam war and how we can and il; we
as students must learn how to play a meaningful role in changing our routing society.
We need to set up more chances for recreation to ease academic pensions. We need
more nonprofit workshops in areas like family planning, marriage, accounting, the
arts. We must change this college to in the catalogue so people will come here and
won't be disappointed. in order to have better communication with the Trustees perhaps every graduation class should select a person to serve a one year term as a
Trustee immedately after graduation. Maybe we can set up a program in which
processors can give students credit for any work they feel is dramatically worthwhile. How many processors visit the classes oi their yellow collected, and ottersuggestions on teaching method? Maybe one class period per semester in each course
should be devoted to a general discussion of education and the problem of learning.
It is not the job of a college to train students in a moral line, but, rather. to
present relevant materials to them so each Student can develop his Own continue.
The Grinneil Weekend for this spring is entitled “The Museum as Tastemaker in
Society”, and I fear it is not the relevant topic it could be. son should, it no else
can, set up programs like Grinnell weekends on drug use, on sexuality, and any
other permanent. interesting topics. Ii we need money, then let's set up a Senate
committee ID work with Mr. prison to get foundation grants for our worthwhile
programs.
Besides using our own ideas, we can communicate and discuss programs with
other schools, remembering, however, that we must bit their programs to our needs,
for by briefly adoption them we also adopt the problems interest With them.
Finally we should look at some oi our newer programs and evaluate them _
interim, no women’s hours, and hopefully, a radio station by Christmas. We must
relate their problems and failures to what we are planning now.
i don’t timing that this is the time or plate for separation. We are not a school
where students and administration and faculty are totally at odds—We do have some
common goals. Our problem now is to pursue them in a context oi meaningful dis
session resulting in programs we need to solve Grinnell adults. This will take community action and work. In our discussions we must recognize the total effect oi our
actions and the ultimate consequences they Will have.
I hope you'll recognize that change is essential and that changes can come best
through work. We must make sure that our demands are truly our needs. Sacrifice
may still be necessary, but it must be based on responsibility and thought. Our attitude must be positive, just as our education must be positive — for it is only
through accentuating the positive that we will succeed in making the Grinnell experience relevant and worthwhile in the context or total community in preparation
for life.
 
